04434nam a22006735i 9780691187501DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20181990nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911875017 a10.1515/97806911875012doi  a(DE-B1597)501576  a(OCoLC)1076461203  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBL80.2.P455 1990b 7aREL0400102bisacsh04a2911 aPeters, F. E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJudaism, Christianity, and Islam: The Classical Texts and Their Interpretation, Volume III :bThe Works of the Spirit /cF. E. Peters. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Brief Chronology -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Worship of God: Temple and Synagogue -- t2. The Worship of God: Church and Mosque -- t3. Withdrawal from the World -- t4.The Mystics' Ascent to God -- t5 . Thinking about God -- t6. The Last Things -- tShort Titles -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInvoking a concept as simple as it is brilliant, F. E. Peters has taken the basic texts of the three related--and competitive--religious systems we call Judaism, Christianity, and Islam and has juxtaposed them in a topical and parallel arrangement according to the issues that most concerned all these "children of Abraham." Through these extensive passages, and the author's skillful connective commentary, the three traditions are shown with their similarities sometimes startlingly underlined and their well-known differences now more profoundly exposed. What emerges from this unique and ambitious work is a panorama of belief, practice, and sensibility that will broaden our understanding of our religious and political roots in a past that is, by these communities' definition, still the present. The hardcover edition of the work is bound in one volume, and in the paperback version the identical material is broken down into three smaller but self-contained books. The third, "The Works of the Spirit," focuses on spirituality and worship and contains material on monasticism, theology, mysticism, and the "End Time." Throughout the work we hear an amazing variety of voices, some familiar, some not, all of them central to the primary and secondary canons of their own tradition: alongside the Scriptural voice of God are the words of theologians, priests, visionaries, lawyers, rulers and the ruled. The work ends, as does the same author's now classic Children of Abraham, in what Peters calls the "classical period," that is, before the great movements of modernism and reform that were to transform Judaism, Christianity, and Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristianity. 0aIslam. 0aJudaism. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187501zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691187501423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187501.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK